## Scope

- Applies to **every user request related to code or features** in this repository **by default**.
- **Opt-out:** "skip workflow" / "kein Workflow", "quick fix" / "nur quick fix", "no merge" / "kein Merge", "nur Erklärung, kein Code", "suggestion only", "explore only" / "nur spike" / "read-only".
- If intent is ambiguous, ask **one concise message** with all open questions before deviating.

**Full playbook:** `.cursor/rules/smash-up-full-workflow-detail.mdc` (Phases 1–14, recovery, stack).

---

## Track pick (before the first implementation edit)

| Goal | Track | First productive edit allowed when |
|------|--------|-------------------------------------|
| Explain / audit / explore only | **Read-only** | Never (readonly tools only until user asks to ship). |
| Small, safe change | **Quick** | Branch from `dev` exists (ticket/plan/roadmap scan skipped). |
| Anything else | **Full** | **Pre-code gate** below is complete. |

**Quick track** — use when the user says quick fix **or** **all** are true: ≤3 files, no DB migration, no new public route/controller, no guest-visible UX change. Still: branch → implement → **tests** (`ddev exec php artisan test` when PHP/app or test code changed; doc-only may run a quick smoke or skip if nothing executable changed) → lint → commit → push → PR → merge (or defer merge; see detail Phase 13).

**Prefer Quick** for typos, single-file fixes, and internal refactors that do not hit the Full triggers — less ticket overhead, same quality gates.

### Track decision (before branch or code edits)

1. Classify **Read-only** vs **Quick** vs **Full** using the trigger matrix and Quick rules.
2. If **Quick** fits and the user did not ask for Full workflow, use **Quick** — do **not** open a ticket or run the Full pre-code gate.
3. **Full** only when a Full trigger applies or scope is unclear until analyzed; then finish the pre-code gate before the first implementation edit.

### First response (when starting a change)

State the track:

> **Full workflow:** Analyze → Ticket → Plan (if triggered) → Branch → Implement → Tests → Lint → Docs (draft) → Browser (if UI) → Docs (finalize) → Commit → Push → PR → Merge → Cleanup. Detail: `.cursor/rules/smash-up-full-workflow-detail.mdc`.

> **Quick track:** Branch → Implement → Tests (when code warrants) → Lint → Commit → Push → PR → Merge (or documented defer).

